Notch expresses interest in a suggestion regarding corals by user "solarblade".

Notch mentioned on his blog: "I tried adding corals, but it's really hard to draw a single block that looks like corals, since it's really more about crazy amounts of variation and diversity. But I do know that the corals will have tiny fish particles around them."
Coral were jokingly teased in the fake snapshot 12marc40awesome, along with fish as mobs and "fish blocks".
Coral fans currently do not generate naturally.
The textures of all coral fans, except fire coral fans, have been changed.
Blue, pink, purple, red, and yellow coral fans have been renamed to tube, brain, bubble, fire, and horn coral fans, respectively.
Coral fans now generate naturally in coral reefs.
5 new sound events that apply to coral fans have been added: block.wet_grass.break, block.wet_grass.fall, block.wet_grass.hit, block.wet_grass.place, and block.wet_grass.step.
Coral fans can now be placed on the tops of blocks.
Coral fans and their dead variants now drop themselves when mined with Silk Touch.
Bone meal used in the water of warm ocean biomes now has a chance of growing coral fans, making them renewable.
Coral fans can be placed on the ground.
The textures of coral fans have been changed.
The textures of dead coral fans have been changed.
The top textures of coral fans have been changed.

texts.text: This article is about the non-solid block. For the original block, see Coral. For other kinds of coral, see Coral (disambiguation).
Coral fans are non-solid blocks that come in 5 variants: tube, brain, bubble, fire, and horn.
Dead coral fans are the dead variants of coral fans.

Coral fans and their dead variants can be mined instantly, but can be obtained only when mined with a Silk Touch enchanted tool. Breaking coral fans without Silk Touch destroys the coral fan.
Dead coral fans can only be obtained with a Silk Touch pickaxe.[1]
Coral fans and dead coral fans naturally generate in coral reef structures.
When bone meal is used in warm ocean biomes, it has a chance of generating coral fans.

In order for coral fans to stay alive, they must be placed in water. In Java Edition, coral fans can also be placed outside of water as long as one of the blocks surrounding it contains water. If placed outside of water, they transform into their respective dead coral fan immediately‌[Bedrock Edition only] or after a few seconds‌[Java Edition only].

Wall coral fans cannot be obtained through vanilla means. In Java Edition, they are completely unobtainable, but in Bedrock Edition, they can be obtained through add-ons or inventory editing, though the item form is badly glitched to the point of being completely nameless.
Coral fans and dead coral fans can be used for building or as a decoration block.
All coral fans (and their dead variants) can be placed on the four sides and the top surface of blocks; they cannot be placed on the bottom surface.

Live coral fans cannot be pushed by pistons (attempting to do so results in the coral fan breaking). Dead coral fans can be pushed by pistons as long as they will still be "supported" in the new position (not floating).
